Canva just hit $4B in revenue and directly credited LLM referral traffic.

https://t.co/zvZUfkYWT4

Here is why all these things are connected:

First let's start with Canva hitting $4B in ARR.

Canva co-founder Cliff Obrecht told TechCrunch that "we really see ChatGPT or any of the LLMs as top-of-the-funnel acquisition platforms.â€

He also added while traditional search is a big traffic source for them, traffic through LLM referrals is in double-digit percentages.

This all makes perfect sense.

Canva explicitly said:

They drove early growth through Google.

They deeply understood search intent.

They built content that mapped to that intent.

That matters because most AI retrieval pipelines still look like this:

Layer 1: 

Search index (Google, Bing, internal index)

Link graph authority

Domain trust

Entity signals

Historical performance

Layer 2: 

Chunking into passages

Vector embeddings

Snippet scoring

Context window assembly

LLM synthesis

If you donâ€™t qualify at Layer 1, you never reach Layer 2.

If you donâ€™t structure content properly at Layer 2, you donâ€™t get quoted.

Canva does well because they qualify at both.

The article also mentions:

26M conversations with Canva inside ChatGPT

Top 10 referred domains from ChatGPT

Double-digit percentage LLM referral traffic

That's all the result of:

Strong brand entity recognition

Clean, extractable landing pages

High link equity

Structured product positioning

Massive search intent coverage

Keep in mind, LLMs are conservative systems and they prefer:

Known entities

Consistent brand descriptions

High-confidence sources

Frequently cited domains

This is retrieval confidence scoring in action.

Now also keep in mind, recent Ahrefs data shows:

Google still sends ~190x more traffic than ChatGPT.

ChatGPTâ€™s CTR is lower.

So why invest in AI visibility?

Well, because LLMs are pre-filter engines.

Users increasingly:

Ask ChatGPT for the shortlist

Then Google the final choice

Then convert

If youâ€™re not cited at step one, you never reach step two.

Thatâ€™s exactly why Canva is investing in both.

This isn't fully set in stone because the reality is that LLMs are smart and will respond even you don't do this in a lot of cases, but best practices include:

Question-based headings

2â€“4 sentence declarative answers

TLDR blocks

Clean HTML

Logical section segmentation (120â€“180 word clusters)

Why?

Because retrieval systems chunk content into embeddings.

Well-structured clusters increase:

Semantic match probability

Snippet selection likelihood

Context window density

Entity clarity includes: 

Organization schema

Product schema

Consistent NAP data

Clear category labeling

Defined use cases

Entity confusion can lead to retrieval exclusion.

Authority propagation includes: 

High-quality backlinks

Mentions in authoritative contexts

Off-site corroboration

Review platforms

Authority still governs retrieval weighting.

All of this validates SEO Stuffâ€™s architecture.

It was built around retrieval mechanics.

This increases:

Embedding density

This is how you move from "a site that ranksâ€ (kind of meaningless unless you're on Page 1) to "a domain that LLMs consistently reuse.â€
